  <title translate="true">Motion-Laws-Standard</title>
  <keywords>
    <keyword translate="true">Motion Definition<keyword translate="true">Standard Motion-Laws</keyword></keyword>
  </keywords>
  <body>
    <para styleclass="" style="text-align:left; text-indent:0px; margin-top:0px; margin-right:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; line-height:1.00; background-color:transparent; white-space:normal; page-break-inside:auto; page-break-after:auto; border:none; tabstops:none;"><table styleclass="MotionPupup" rowcount="1" colcount="1">
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="Interface" translate="true">Traditional Motion-Laws </text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">are those motions that have been used for many years in Industrial Cams. These motion-laws frequently have a Dwell Segment before and after them. The velocity and acceleration is usually zero at the start and end.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">They are usually fixed-order Polynomials (for example, 3-4-5 Polynomial) or based on a combination of other laws (for example, the Modified Trapezoidal).</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="Popup Box" style="font-style:normal;" translate="true">They are historically important.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Normal"><line style="height:1px; color:#993300;" /></para>
